<div id="content"><a name="contentJump"></a>


<div class="welcome">
Welcome to ECS, the School  of Electronics and Computer Science at the University of Southampton. ECS is one of the world's leading centres for 
<a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/research/">research</a>, 
<a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/about/teaching/">teaching</a>, <a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/business/">enterprise and innovation</a> in Electronics, Electrical Engineering and Computer Science.
<div class="sig">Head of School: <a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/people/wh">Professor Wendy Hall</a></div>
</div>


<div class="headline"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/449"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_449_img&amp;maxw=200&amp;maxh=150&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=65b0b249c39d1eaaeb12d4157658d677" alt="Neil Palmer demonstrates the power of the HV Lab" border="0" width="200" height="135" class="thumbnail" /></a><h2>Headline News</h2><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/449">Power engineers switch to unique new lab</a></h3><p>Last year's widely disruptive power cuts in the UK, Europe and the United States demonstrated the extent to which we rely on electricity, and the catastrophic consequences to all aspects of our lives when the supply fails. A unique facility being opened this week at the University of Southampton is intended to help avoid these damaging incidents by providing the specialized research and testing facilities on which the power supply industry depends.</p></div><div id='contentMain'>
<hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/443"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_443_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=1dbda7164e61bccbc99362922568e757" alt="James Wilkinson, Ping Hua and Patrick Hole" border="0" width="120" height="79" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/443">European water directive: optical sensors tackle pollutants</a></h3><p>Minute amounts of organic pollutants, including oestrone, can now be detected in river water as a result of a new optical sensing instrument realised in a project funded by the EU's Environment Programme. Professor James Wilkinson, left, with Ping Hua and Patrick Hole, of the Optoelectronics Research Centre, leads one of the AWACSS research teams which have developed the new instrument.</p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/442"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_442_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=418537f104d903745802ace814163417" alt="University Concert Hall" border="0" width="120" height="92" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/442">Keyboard magic, from concert pianos to computers</a></h3><p>Researchers at the universities of Southampton and Vienna have demonstrated that the complex and individual performance styles of concert pianists such as Glenn Gould and Vladimir Horowitz can be modelled in unique "performance alphabets", providing a method of recognizing their performance styles by computer, and also, possibly, reconstructing them.</p></div><hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/438"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_438_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=95aac39482232e5039594ad3cd44ca41" alt="ECS staff and new graduates 2004" border="0" width="120" height="90" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/438">Graduation 2004</a></h3><p>Over 300 ECS students received their degrees at this year's graduation ceremonies. Addressing the guests at the reception and prize-giving ceremonies which followed Graduation, Professor Wendy Hall, Head of School, congratulated the new graduates on their achievements, and urged them to stay in touch with the School in the future.</p><p></p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/436"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_436_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=01566c1f8f0e3a020b5a49987d831eeb" alt="Professor Lajos Hanzo and his son Lajos" border="0" width="110" height="120" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/436">Double honours for Lajos Hanzo</a></h3><p>This week's graduation ceremony at the University of Southampton sees a double celebration for Professor of Telecommunications, Lajos Hanzo. Not only will Professor Hanzo be awarded a higher doctorate (DSc) by the University for his distinguished lifetime research in adaptive wireless communications systems, but at the same ceremony his son, also named Lajos Hanzo, will receive a First Class Master of Computer Engineering degree.</p><p></p></div><p class="clearBoth"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20040915075314/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/">More News</a></p></div>

